---
title: Chicken & Chickpea Tabbouleh Bowls with Creamy Feta Dressing
description: We’re big fans of the ubiquitous “power bowl,” but we have to admit: This one’s extra special. It’s a one-bowl Middle Eastern–style feast that’s positively bursting with flavor. The base is a lemony bulgur salad with cucumber, tomato, scallion whites, and dill. On top, there’s crispy, harissa-spiced chickpeas, bell pepper, and a drizzle of creamy feta dressing. It doesn’t get much better than this!
image: https://img.hellofresh.com/f_auto,fl_lossy,h_640,q_auto,w_1200/hellofresh_s3/image/63fe2bbbe0f70881df0a8a93-6330222e.jpg
pdf: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipecards/card/65e89b24ad357710d5d54c72.pdf
nutrition:
  calories: 1000 kcal
  fat: 52 g
  saturated fat: 13 g
  carbohydrates: 83 g
  sugar: 12 g
  protein: 51 g
  fiber: 15 g
  sodium: 1540 mg
cuisine: Mediterranean
servings: 2
author: HelloFresh
course: main course
time required: 30 minutes
source: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipes/chicken-and-chickpea-tabbouleh-bowls-65e89b24ad357710d5d54c72
---

Adjust rack to top position (top and middle positions for 4 servings) and preheat
oven to 425 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Core, deseed, and dice @bell pepper{1} into ½-inch pieces. Drain and rinse
@chickpeas{1%400g can}; pat very dry with #paper towels{}.

Toss bell pepper and chickpeas on a #baking sheet{} with a large drizzle of
@olive oil{1%tsp}, @harissa powder{1%tsp} (2 tsp for 4 servings), and @salt{}.
(You'll use more harissa powder in the next step.) (For 4, divide between 2
baking sheets; roast on top and middle racks.)

Roast on top rack until bell pepper is softened and chickpeas are lightly
browned, ~{18-20%minutes}. (It's natural for chickpeas to pop a bit while
roasting.)

While bell pepper and chickpeas roast, in a #small pot{}, combine
@bulgur wheat{1/2%cup}, @water{1%cup}, @harissa powder{1/2%tsp} (be sure to
measure), and @salt{1/2%tsp} (we used ½ tsp). (For 4 servings, use 2 cups water,
1 tsp harissa powder; we used 1 tsp salt.) Bring to a boil, then cover and
reduce to a low simmer. Cook until water has absorbed and bulgur is tender,
~{12-15%minutes}.

Keep covered off heat until ready to use in step 5.

While bulgur cooks, open package of @diced chicken thighs{10%oz} and drain off
any excess liquid. Season chicken all over with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Heat a
drizzle of @cooking oil{1%tsp} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add
chicken and cook, stirring occasionally, until opaque and cooked through,
~{4-6%minutes}.

Meanwhile, zest and halve @lemon{1}. Trim and finely dice @mini cucumber{1} and
@tomato{1}. Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2}, separating whites from greens;
mince whites. Pick and mince fronds from @dill{1/4%ounce}.

In a #small bowl{}, whisk together @sour cream{3%tbsp}, @feta cheese{2%tbsp}, and
@olive oil{1%tbsp}. (You'll use the remaining feta in the next step.) Add
water @water{1%tsp} at a time until mixture reaches a drizzling consistency.
Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Squeeze juice from one lemon half (juice from whole lemon for 4 servings) into a
#large bowl{}. Whisk in lemon zest, @olive oil{2%tbsp}, and @salt{1/4%tsp}
(we used ¼ tsp; ½ tsp for 4).

If necessary, drain any excess water from bulgur, then stir into bowl along
with cucumber, tomato, scallion whites, remaining @feta cheese{2%tbsp}, and
minced dill to taste (start with half and add more from there if desired). Taste
and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Divide tabbouleh between #bowls{}. Top with roasted bell pepper and chickpeas.
Drizzle with feta dressing and sprinkle with scallion greens. Cut any remaining
lemon into wedges and serve on the side.

Serve chicken atop bowls.

> Chicken is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 165º.